04699nam a2200721Ia 9781782046318DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20162016xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817820463187 a10.1515/97817820463182doi  a(DE-B1597)676376  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aMUS0060002bisacsh04a780.92qOCoLC223/eng/202302161 aPyke, Cameron, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBenjamin Britten and Russia /cCameron Pyke. 1aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (383 p.) :b27 b/w, 30 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAldeburgh Studies in Music ;v1100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbbreviations -- tNote on Transliteration and Sources -- t1 Earliest and Lifelong Russophilia -- t2 Britten and Shostakovich, 1934–63 -- t3 Britten and Prokofiev -- t4 Britten and Stravinsky -- t5 Hospitality and Politics -- t6 Pushkin and Performance -- t7 Britten and Shostakovich Again: Dialogues of War and Death, 1963–76 -- tConclusion -- tAppendices -- tBibliography and Sources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExplores Benjamin Britten's deeply-felt cultural affinity with Russia and influences on the 'Russian' Britten.This book explores Benjamin Britten's creative relationship with Russia throughout his life by examining his engagement with Russian composers, musicians and writers in the context of twentieth-century politics. The remarkable relationship between Britten and Shostakovich is a central theme, but it also evaluates other key influences, particularly Britten's passion for Tchaikovsky, his more elusive fascination with Prokofiev, and his ambiguous attitude towards Stravinsky; and it places Britten's enduring friendships with Rostropovich, Vishnevskaya and Richter in the context of his musical output. The book also analyses Britten's responses to various Russian composers and musicians- why, for example, did he dislike Musorgsky? - and considers personal and political perceptions of Britten in the Soviet Union. Finally, it assesses the wider question of Russian influence on Britten's works and in turn whether Britten's music had any influence on the younger generation of Russian composers, such as Alfred Schnittke. This study draws on Foreign Office and British Council files at the National Archives, published and unpublished material from the former Soviet Union, including the Shostakovich Family Archive, and oral history, in addition to the Britten-related archives. Benjamin Britten and Russia will appeal not only to Britten scholars and students but also to those interested in twentieth-century culture, history and politics more widely. CAMERON PYKE is Deputy Master (External) at Dulwich College and part-time lecturer at the Centre of Russian Music, Goldsmiths, University of London.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh  aArt History.  aBenjamin Britten.  aBiography.  aChamber music.  aChoral.  aComposer.  aConductor.  aDmitri Shostakovich.  aHistory.  aMusic history.  aMusic.  aOpera.  aOrchestra.  aPianist.  aPolitics.  aRussia.  aRussian Politics.  aSoviet Union.  aTchaikovsky.  aTwentieth-Century.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311143131440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204631840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782046318423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782046318/original  a978-3-11-143131-4  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles